3":"1590–1683","1549–1613":"1549–1613","1613":"1613","22 November 1613":"22. november 1613","1586":"1586","1630":"1630","1683":"1683","1550":"1550","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, Massachusetts":"Middlesex, Massachusetts, Amerikas Forenede Stater","of Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1549–22 November 1613":"1549–22 november 1613","1550–Male":"1550–Overleden","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1590–1683":"1590–1683","1549–1613":"1549–1613","1613":"1613","22 November 1613":"22 november 1613","1586":"1586","1630":"1630","1683":"1683","1550":"1550","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Halstead, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, Massachusetts":"Middlesex, Massachusetts, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","of Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1549–22 November 1613":"1549–22 November 1613","1550–Male":"1550–Deceased","1586–1630":"1586–1630","1590–1683":"1590–1683","1549–1613":"1549–1613","1613":"1613","22 November 1613":"22 November 1613","1586":"1586","1630":"1630","1683":"1683","1550":"1550","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, Massachusetts":"Middlesex, Massachusetts, United States","of Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carrier","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Lucien, Cecile, Alain, Gaetan, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Normand.","English and southern French: from Middle English, Old French <i>car(r)ier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carrarius</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart, wagon’, a word of Gaulish origin), an occupational name for a carter (see   Carter  ), in French also for a cartwright. Compare French   Charrier  .","French: occupational name for a stonemason or quarryman, <i>carrier</i>. Compare   Coyer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carter","meanings":["English: occupational name for a transporter of goods, from Middle English <i>carter(e)</i> ‘carter’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>car(e)tier</i>, Old French <i>charetier</i>, medieval Latin <i>carettarius</i>, <i>carettator</i>). The Old French word coalesced with the earlier Middle English word <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’, which is from either Old Norse <i>kartr</i> or Old English <i>cræt</i>, both of which, like the Late Latin word, were probably derived from Celtic. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarter  .","Americanized form of German   Karter   ‘carder’."]},{"name":"Coyer","meanings":["Altered form of French   Carrier  .","French: from a derivative of Latin <i>cos</i>, genitive <i>cotis</i>, denoting the pouch where a reaper kept a whetstone for sharpening his sickle, hence a metonymic occupational name for a reaper or mower.","French: alternatively, perhaps a habitational name from La Couyère, a place in Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany (France)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret Carrier was born in 1549, in Halstead, Essex, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Rodger Toothaker. She died on 22 November 1613, in Middlesex, Massachusetts, United States, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1549–22 November 1613":"1549–22. novemb